  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are specific laws targeting money laundering in many countries around the world. These laws are designed to prevent the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (dirty money) appear legal by disguising their true origins. In the United States, the primary law targeting money laundering is the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** of 1970, which has been amended and expanded over the years. Additionally, the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)** of 1986 explicitly made money laundering a federal crime.\n\nOther countries have their own specific laws:\n\n1. **United Kingdom:** The **Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA)** 2002 is the primary legislation addressing money laundering. It criminalizes various forms of money laundering and provides law enforcement with tools to confiscate the proceeds of crime.\n\n2. **European Union:** The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Directives, with the **Sixth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)** being the most recent as of the last update. These directives require member states to implement comprehensive AML regulations.\n\n3. **Canada:** The **Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act (PCMLTFA)** is the main law targeting money laundering in Canada.\n\n4. **Australia:** The **Anti-Mo",
